## Detailed Implementation Plan

### Overview

Add a specialized chat template handler for "Mistral Instruct v0.3" (the `[INST]`/`[/INST]` format without tool calling, system prompt prepended to first user turn) in the Jinja handler system within `common/chat.cpp`. This handler is content-only (no tool calling), making it one of the simplest possible handlers.

### 1. Detection Criteria in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Location**: `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775499895165-dbprgz/common/chat.cpp`, line 1688 (just before `return std::nullopt;` at line 1690)

**Detection logic**: The Mistral v1/v0.2/v0.3 Jinja template source has these distinguishing characteristics compared to other `[INST]`-based templates:
- Contains `[INST]` -- identifies it as an `[INST]`/`[/INST]`-family template
- Does NOT contain `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` -- distinguishes from Mistral v7 and Ministral 3 (which the Ministral 3 handler already checks for, but this provides a clean negative guard)
- Does NOT contain `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` -- distinguishes from Mistral v3, v3-tekken, and Nemo templates which have native tool calling
- Does NOT contain `<<SYS>>` -- distinguishes from Llama 2 variants

**Placement**: Insert at the **end** of the detection chain, just before `return std::nullopt;` at line 1690. This is the safest position because:
- All existing handlers check for tokens that this template does NOT have, so ordering doesn't matter for correctness
- Placing it last means it only activates when no other handler matched, minimizing collision risk

**Code to insert** (at line 1688, after the GigaChat block's closing brace):

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 (v1 template format) - simple [INST]/[/INST] format without tool calling
    // Detection: has [INST] but not [SYSTEM_PROMPT] (v7), not [AVAILABLE_TOOLS] (v3/tekken), not <<SYS>> (llama2)
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("<<SYS>>") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

### 2. Handler Function Implementation

**Location**: Insert a new static function in `common/chat.cpp`, before the `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` function (i.e., around line 1633, between the `common_chat_extra_context()` function and the detection function). Alternatively, place it near the other Mistral handler (after `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3` at line 940).

**Recommended placement**: Line ~1519 (after `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` ends at line 1517, before the `namespace workaround` block at line 1519). This keeps it adjacent to the other recent specialized handlers.

Actually, the best placement is immediately before `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, around line 1633. This keeps it close to where it's called and follows the pattern of the file where handlers are defined before the dispatch function.

**Handler structure** -- this is a content-only handler (no tool calling) since Mistral v0.3 does not have native tool call syntax:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template & tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {

    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**Why this is sufficient**:
- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs)` renders the Jinja template into the full prompt string (including `[INST]`/`[/INST]` wrapping, system message prepending, and `</s>` after assistant turns). The Jinja template handles all the formatting.
- The PEG parser just needs to capture everything after the generation prompt as content, since there are no tool calls to parse.
- `data.supports_thinking = false` because this template has no thinking/reasoning markers.
- No `data.preserved_tokens` needed because the parser is content-only (no delimiters to preserve during streaming).
- No grammar, grammar_triggers, or grammar_lazy needed since there's no tool calling.

### 3. Jinja Template File

**File**: Create `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja`

This file should contain the Jinja template source for the Mistral v1 format. Based on the test vector at line 529-530 of `tests/test-chat-template.cpp`, the template is:

