**Handler structure** -- this is a content-only handler (no tool calling) since Mistral v0.3 does not have native tool call syntax:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template & tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {

    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**Why this is sufficient**:
- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs)` renders the Jinja template into the full prompt string (including `[INST]`/`[/INST]` wrapping, system message prepending, and `</s>` after assistant turns). The Jinja template handles all the formatting.
- The PEG parser just needs to capture everything after the generation prompt as content, since there are no tool calls to parse.
- `data.supports_thinking = false` because this template has no thinking/reasoning markers.
- No `data.preserved_tokens` needed because the parser is content-only (no delimiters to preserve during streaming).
