# Plan: Add "mistral-instruct-v3" Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 uses a simple `[INST]`/`[/INST]` format: system messages are prepended to the first user turn (separated by `\n\n`), and `</s>` is appended after assistant turns. There is no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` wrapping and no native tool-calling syntax. Currently this format has no dedicated specialized handler in the Jinja path (`common/chat.cpp`), so it falls through to the autoparser. Adding an explicit handler ensures reliable, deterministic behavior.

## Files to Modify / Create

| File | Action |
|------|--------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Add handler function + detection clause |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja` | Create new Jinja template file |
| `tests/test-chat.cpp` | Add PEG parser test case |

**Not modified**: `src/llama-chat.h` (header), no existing handler code is changed.

---

## Step 1: Create Jinja template file

**File**: `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja` (new file)

Contains the Mistral v1-style Jinja template (matching the template string at `tests/test-chat-template.cpp:530`):

```jinja
{%- if messages[0]['role'] == 'system' %}
    {%- set system_message = messages[0]['content'] %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages[1:] %}
{%- else %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages %}
{%- endif %}

{{- bos_token }}
{%- for message in loop_messages %}
    {%- if (message['role'] == 'user') != (loop.index0 % 2 == 0) %}
        {{- raise_exception('After the optional system message, conversation roles must alternate user/assistant/user/assistant/...') }}
    {%- endif %}
    {%- if message['role'] == 'user' %}
        {%- if loop.first and system_message is defined %}
            {{- ' [INST] ' + system_message + '\n\n' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- else %}
            {{- ' [INST] ' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]' }}
        {%- endif %}
    {%- elif message['role'] == 'assistant' %}
        {{- ' ' + message['content'] + eos_token}}
    {%- else %}
        {{- raise_exception('Only user and assistant roles are supported, with the exception of an initial optional system message!') }}
    {%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}
```

Key format traits:
- `' [INST] ' + system + '\n\n' + user + ' [/INST]'` (first turn with system)
- `' [INST] ' + user + ' [/INST]'` (subsequent turns)
- `' ' + assistant + eos_token` (assistant turns)

---

## Step 2: Add handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

**Insert at**: ~line 1633, immediately before `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`.

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template & tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {

    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

Rationale:
- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` renders the Jinja template into the full prompt (with `[INST]`/`[/INST]` wrapping, system prepend, `</s>` after assistant).
- PEG parser: content-only (`p.content(p.rest())`) since the format has no tool-calling tokens to parse.
- No `preserved_tokens`, no grammar, no tool triggers needed.

---

## Step 3: Add detection clause in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Insert at**: line ~1689 in `common/chat.cpp`, just before `return std::nullopt;` (after all existing handlers).

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 - simple [INST]/[/INST] format, system prepended to first user turn
    // Distinguish from Ministral 3 (has [SYSTEM_PROMPT]), Mistral Nemo/v3 (has [AVAILABLE_TOOLS]),
    // and Llama 2 (has <<SYS>>)
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("<<SYS>>") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

Detection logic:
- `[INST]` present: identifies it as Mistral/INST-family
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent: not Ministral 3 / Mistral v7
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` absent: not Mistral Nemo / v3-tekken (which have native tool calling)
- `<<SYS>>` absent: not Llama 2

Placed last so more specific handlers always match first.

---

## Step 4: Add test in `tests/test-chat.cpp`

**Insert at**: line ~3148, after the Mistral-Nemo test block's closing brace.

```cpp
    // mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 (Mistral Instruct v3, content-only)
    {
        auto tst = peg_tester("models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja", detailed_debug);
        tst.test("Hello, world!\nWhat's up?").expect(message_assist).expect_reconstruction().run();
    }
```

This tests:
1. The specialized handler is selected (via detection criteria matching the template)
2. Content-only PEG parsing works correctly
3. Reconstruction round-trips properly

---

## Verification

```bash
# Build the test binary
cmake -B build && cmake --build build --target test-chat

# Run all tests (includes the new test)
./build/bin/test-chat

# Also run the template test manually on the new template
./build/bin/test-chat-template models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja
```

Expected: all tests pass, the new handler is selected for the Mistral v0.3 template (visible via `LOG_DBG` output: "Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3").

